{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RkyvNNYarReQTP2d7hH4xW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the email drafting assistant issue.\n\n**Behavior 1: The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does this require multiple modules? The core failure here is whether the LLM actually references specific points. You could test this with a unit test that checks some parsing logic, but the real failure is whether the LLM actually uses the email content.\n- LLM-DEP: YES - correctness depends on what a real LLM produces. Whether the reply references specific points is a quality judgment about LLM output. You can't mock the LLM and verify this - a mock would always return a pre-crafted response that references the email.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the LLM would always pass since you'd hard-code a response that references the email.\n- Minimum level: **Agentic** - because the test needs to verify that the real LLM actually uses the email context.\n\n**Behavior 2: The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.**\n\nFor the consistency checker, I need to determine if it's an LLM call. Factual consistency checking typically relies on an LLM to compare claims against the knowledge base, which means this also depends on real LLM behavior and can't be properly mocked.\n\nThe key question is whether this is semantic reasoning (LLM-based, Agentic) or just deterministic keyword matching (Integration). Given that we're dealing with an autonomous email drafting assistant that uses LLMs, the consistency check is almost certainly semantic rather than rule-based. I'll classify this as **Agentic** since the ability to catch contradictions depends on the real model's understanding.\n\nFor the third behavior about adding disclaimers when the knowledge base has no relevant entries—this involves both control flow logic (detecting when KB returns nothing) and LLM behavior (whether the model actually avoids fabrication even when instructed). The tricky part is that an LLM might still hallucinate facts despite being told to add a disclaimer instead.\n\nThe real question is whether the failure comes from the code not triggering the disclaimer logic at all, or from the LLM ignoring the instruction and fabricating anyway. Testing the control flow alone with mocks isn't enough—you need the actual LLM to verify it genuinely follows the disclaimer instruction rather than making up facts.\n\nFor behavior 4, this is purely about workflow control—whether the system actually blocks sending until explicit approval. It's not dependent on LLM output quality, and while real email infrastructure might be involved, the test itself is just checking whether the send operation is gated behind approval, not whether the email actually gets delivered.\n\nFor behavior 5, this is a multi-step workflow that chains together reading the thread, generating a draft via LLM, fact-checking, and presenting for approval—multiple agentic steps in sequence means this needs to be tested at the Workflow level.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence scores across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 requires a real LLM to verify that replies actually reference specific points from the thread, so Agentic testing dominates at 0.85. Behavior 2 is similar—detecting contradictions needs the real checker, giving Agentic a 0.80 probability, though Integration could work if the checker is rule-based. Behavior 3 follows the same pattern.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the approval workflow is more testable at the Integration level since I can wire the approval and send modules together, making that 0.75. Behavior 5 is the full end-to-end sequence, which is almost entirely a Workflow test at 0.85 since it requires all components running together.\n\nNow I'm writing out the specific test cases for each behavior. For Behavior 1, I need to submit a real email thread with concrete details to the LLM reply generator and verify it references specific entities from the email rather than generic responses. For Behavior 2, I'll seed the knowledge base with factual entries, then submit a draft with contradicting claims to the consistency checker and confirm it flags the contradiction. For Behavior 3, I'm configuring the knowledge base to return no results, submitting an email that needs domain-specific facts to the draft generator, and verifying the output includes a disclaimer and doesn't make unfounded assertions.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm initializing the approval workflow with a generated draft and confirming the send function doesn't execute until approval is submitted, then verifying it's called exactly once after approval. For Behavior 5, I'm running a real email thread through the entire pipeline—parsing, LLM draft generation, consistency checking, and approval—to ensure all steps execute in sequence and the draft is contextual while factual issues are caught.\n\nLooking at the consistency of each test against the plan, the first three are agentic tests requiring real LLM components, the fourth is an integration test using mocked send with wired approval and send modules, and the fifth is a workflow test running multiple agentic steps sequentially.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9418,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9418},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"108cdae9-48c8-4ce4-a084-0deee14d1698","uuid":"5f3797e6-1bc9-42db-b7bc-e915b2312669"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RkyvNNYarReQTP2d7hH4xW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KH2CKWF4rCbV61xt4e2e3F","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is not a module handoff bug — it is whether the real LLM uses the email context. LLM-DEP: A mocked LLM trivially returns a pre-crafted contextual reply, hiding the failure entirely. MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic stub passes by construction. Only a real LLM call can reveal whether the model actually grounds its reply in the thread content.","test_description":"Submit a real email thread containing specific named entities, dates, and topics to the LLM-based reply generator. Assert that the returned draft contains at least N of those specific items (e.g., names, figures, dates) and does not consist solely of generic filler phrases unrelated to the thread.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Factual consistency checking in this pipeline is semantically driven — it must understand that a claim contradicts a KB entry, not just that a keyword differs. A deterministic stub would always flag or never flag, masking real failure. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the checker returns a pre-set flag regardless of actual claim–KB relationship. The real failure (model fails to detect semantic contradiction) only surfaces with a live model call.","test_description":"Seed the knowledge base with specific factual entries (e.g., 'Product X was released in 2022'). Submit a draft containing a direct contradiction ('Product X was released in 2019') to the consistency checker backed by a real model. Assert the checker returns a flag or warning identifying the contradicting claim, and does not flag a non-contradicting claim about the same product.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The failure mode is that the real LLM ignores the 'no KB results' signal and asserts fabricated specifics anyway. Integration-level testing with a mocked LLM trivially passes by returning a pre-written disclaimer. MOCK-HIDE: Only a real LLM call reveals whether the model respects the empty-KB condition or hallucinates instead.","test_description":"Configure the knowledge base retrieval to return zero results for the query topic. Submit a domain-specific email thread to the real LLM-based draft generator. Assert the output contains a disclaimer phrase (e.g., 'I'm not certain', 'please verify') and does not assert specific factual claims (dates, figures, named entities) that were absent from both the email thread and the KB.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a control-flow bug at the module boundary between the approval state machine and the send module — a real module-handoff failure, not a single-function logic bug. LLM-DEP: LLM output quality is irrelevant; the test is about whether send() is ever called before approval is recorded. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the send function and asserting it is not called is appropriate here — the dependency being mocked (email transport) is not what is under test. No LLM or OS/network behavior is needed.","test_description":"Instantiate the approval workflow with a pre-generated draft (no LLM needed). Assert that the send function (mocked via patch.object) is not called when the workflow is advanced without an approval event. Then submit an explicit approval action and assert send is called exactly once with the draft content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names multiple agentic steps in sequence: thread ingestion → LLM draft generation → LLM/model-based fact check → approval gate. Each step with a real model can fail independently, and inter-step state handoff (draft content, KB flags, approval status) can be lost between steps. No single step or module pair captures this; only a full pipeline run does.","test_description":"Feed a real email thread into the full pipeline. Observe in order: thread is parsed and passed to the LLM; the LLM returns a draft; the draft is passed to the fact checker with the real KB; any flagged claims are surfaced; the pipeline halts at the approval gate. Assert that (a) the draft references the thread, (b) KB contradictions are flagged if seeded, and (c) no send occurs until an explicit approval is injected into the pipeline.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.85}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9418,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9418},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"108cdae9-48c8-4ce4-a084-0deee14d1698","uuid":"bd68e9fd-e9e9-45d4-af4f-b614bd0c3538"}
